The article discusses how fentanyl, a synthetic painkiller that is 50 times more powerful than heroin, has become a major drug problem in the United States. The article highlights how a group of health experts in 2016 urged the Obama administration to declare fentanyl a national public health emergency, but the administration did not take action. Between 2013 and 2017, over 67,000 people died from synthetic opioid overdoses, with fentanyl being the leading cause. The article suggests that an emergency declaration could have helped raise awareness and saved lives. The article also mentions the Obama administration's response to other health emergencies, such as the Zika virus, and the global threat posed by counterfeit pain pills laced with fentanyl.